### Introduction

We have studied the kinematics of bodies in (i) straight line, (ii) projectile and (iii) circular motions.

Oscillatory motions are another type of motion that can be often seen in everyday life: the swinging pendulum of a grandfather clock, the vibrations of a bus, and the waves on the strings of a guitar. Other non-visible examples include the electro-magnetic oscillations emitted by wireless equipment, gaseous atoms and molecules that propagate sound waves, and the lattice vibrations of atoms.

To better understand how these systems work, it is important we learn the mechanics of oscillations.

